This paper discusses the limitations of traditional impact factors and proposes a new method for contextualizing citations at the paper level. The paper focuses on the field of science and discusses the impact of different journals, which suggests that it could be relevant to several sub-categories of computer science. Specifically, the discussion of citation behavior and normalization decisions suggests that it could be relevant to sub-categories such as digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), and machine learning (cs.LG). The focus on measuring the impact of journals and papers also suggests that it could be relevant to sub-categories such as social and information networks (cs.SI) and cybernetics (cs.CY).
